SIMPLE: loop
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loop
<hw>Loop</hw> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧p)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G.
<ets>luppe</ets> an iron lump. Cf. <er>Looping</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Iron
Works)</fld> <def>A mass of iron in a pasty condition gathered into a
ball for the tilt hammer or rolls.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>loup</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Loop
<hw>Loop</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Ir. & Gael. <ets>lub</ets> loop,
noose, fold, thong, bend, <ets>lub</ets> to bend, incline.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A fold or doubling of a thread, cord, rope, etc.,
through which another thread, cord, etc., can be passed, or which a hook
can be hooked into; an eye, as of metal; a staple; a noose; a
bight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That the probation bear no hinge, nor <qex>loop</qex>⟦br⟧
To hang a doubt on.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small, narrow opening; a loophole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And stop all sight-holes, every <qex>loop</qex> from whence⟦br⟧
The eye of Reason may pry in upon us.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A curve of any kind in the form of a loop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Telegraphy)</fld> <def>A wire forming part of a
main circuit and returning to the point from which it starts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Acoustics)</fld> <def>The portion of a vibrating
string, air column, etc., between two nodes; -- called also
<altname>ventral segment</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Loop knot</b></col>, <cd>a single knot tied in a doubled
cord, etc. so as to leave a loop beyond the knot. See <xex>Illust.</xex>
of <er>Knot</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Loop
<hw>Loop</hw> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧p)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Looped</conjf> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧pt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Looping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make a loop of or
in; to fasten with a loop or loops; -- often with <xex>up</xex>; <as>as,
to <ex>loop</ex> a string; to <ex>loop</ex> up a curtain.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Looped</ent>⟦br⟧
